5. Suggested Laravel Route Group
Route::prefix('superadmin')    ->middleware(['auth:sanctum', 'role:superadmin'])    ->group(function () {        Route::get('/dashboard/stats', [SuperAdminDashboardController::class, 'stats']);        Route::apiResource('/products', ProductController::class);        Route::apiResource('/categories', CategoryController::class);        Route::apiResource('/orders', SuperAdminOrderController::class);        Route::apiResource('/franchises', FranchiseController::class);        Route::get('/stock-requests', [StockRequestController::class, 'index']);    });Route::prefix('franchise')    ->middleware(['auth:sanctum', 'role:franchise_admin'])    ->group(function () {        Route::get('/dashboard/stats', [FranchiseDashboardController::class, 'stats']);        Route::get('/orders', [FranchiseOrderController::class, 'index']);        Route::put('/orders/{id}/status', [FranchiseOrderController::class, 'updateStatus']);        Route::get('/products', [FranchiseProductController::class, 'index']);        Route::get('/inventory', [FranchiseInventoryController::class, 'index']);        Route::post('/stock-requests', [FranchiseStockRequestController::class, 'store']);    });

6. Most Important Backend Security Rule
For Franchise Admin APIs, never trust frontend franchise_id.
Use this backend logic:
$franchiseId = auth()->user()->franchise->id;
Then filter everything:
Order::where('franchise_id', $franchiseId)->get();
This prevents one franchise admin from accessing another franchise’s orders, customers, inventory, and payments.